Put a large #saucepan{} of water on to the boil for the noodles. Halve, then remove
the core from the @bell pepper{1} and thinly slice. Trim the @pak choi{150%g}.
Thinly slice widthways. Trim the @green beans{150%g} and chop into thirds. Peel
and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}). Halve the
@red chilli{1/2}, deseed and finely chop. Roughly chop the @coriander{1}(stalks
and all). Chop the @lime{1/2} into wedges.

When the water is boiling, add the @egg noodle nest{2} and cook for ~{4%minutes}.
When cooked, drain in a #colander{}, then cool under cold running water to
stop them cooking any more. Leave to one side.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} or #wok{} on medium heat. Add
the @Kuala Lumpur style curry powder{1}, garlic and @ginger puree{1/2}
along with a pinch of @?chilli{}, if using (don't add too much here - you can
always add more later if it needs more kick!). Stir-fry until fragrant,
~{30%seconds}.

Pour the @coconut milk{200%ml}, @soy sauce{12.5%ml} and a squeeze of lime juice
into the pan. Stir together, bring to the boil then reduce the heat to medium
and simmer until reduced slightly and thickened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Add the pepper and green beans to the sauce and continue to simmer for
~{3-4%minutes}. Stir in the pak choi and cook for a further ~{3-4%minutes}.

> The veggies should be cooked through but still with a little bite - this is a
> fresh and crisp sauce!

Toss the noodles and half the coriander through your sauce until piping hot.
Season to taste with @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed and add extra chilli or
lime if you feel it needs it. Serve in #bowls{} with the remaining coriander
sprinkled on top and any remaining lime wedges for squeezing over. Enjoy!